{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff780fe2-b6c3-46da-9e26-821226338cb1","content":"The template has a solid foundation but has a few issues to address before publishing:\n\n**Critical:**\n- **Missing `$schema`** — Add `\"$schema\": \"http://json.schemastore.org/template\"` for validation support.\n- **No `description`** — Required for NuGet gallery discoverability; users won't know what the template does.\n- **`Framework` symbol has no `replaces`** — The parameter won't substitute into your `.csproj`'s `<TargetFramework>`. Add `\"replaces\": \"net9.0\"` (or a dedicated placeholder) so the chosen value is actually applied.\n\n**Recommended:**\n- **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Needed for template updates and multi-template packs to resolve correctly (e.g., `\"groupIdentity\": \"MyCompany.WebApi\"`).\n- **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Typically `true` for project templates so `dotnet new mywebapi -n Foo` creates a `Foo/` directory.\n\n**Nice-to-have:**\n- Add `\"defaultName\"` (e.g., `\"MyWebApi\"`) to control the fallback project name.\n\nThe `Framework` symbol issue is the most important — without `replaces`, the user's framework choice is silently ignored.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c1431c8d-c51f-4d86-bd99-308efeb325e5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me review this template.json for NuGet publishing readiness. I'll check for required and recommended fields.\n\nIssues I can spot:\n\n1. **Missing `$schema`** — Not strictly required, but highly recommended for validation. The standard schema URL is `https://json.schemastore.org/template.json`.\n\n2. **Missing `groupIdentity`** — Recommended for NuGet packages, especially when bundling multiple templates or for template updates to work correctly.\n\n3. **Missing `precedence`** — Related to groupIdentity, helps with versioning.\n\n4. **Missing `preferNameDirectory`** — Minor, but commonly set for project templates.\n\n\n5. **Framework symbol lacks `replaces`** — The Framework parameter has choices defined but no `replaces` property pointing to where it should substitute in the `.csproj` file, so the selection won't actually affect the `<TargetFramework>` element. That's a functional issue.\n\n6. **Missing `description`** — This is critical for NuGet gallery visibility. Without it, potential users won't understand what the template provides.\n\n7. **No `defaultName`** — A minor omission that affects the default project naming behavior.\n\nThese are the main problems I'm seeing.","outputTokens":657,"requestId":"280F:291A22:F8FCAA:1393AC6:69FFD9B9"},"id":"9bfdd3c6-2a5d-4b6f-b673-1d447a0045c6","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:05:14.058Z","parentId":"bdbaa21e-d347-4fcf-bf8f-de2543b46555"}
